'''Moïse Kapenda Tshombe''' (sometimes written Tshombé) (10 November 1919 – 29 June 1969) was a Congolese businessman and politician. He served as the president of the secessionist [[State of Katanga]] from 1960 to 1963 and as prime minister of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] from 1964 to 1965.

== Early life ==
A member of the [[Lunda people|Lunda tribes]], Tshombe was born near [[Musumba]], [[Belgian Congo]], the son of a successful businessman. He received his education from an American [[missionary]] school and later trained as an accountant. In the 1950s, he took over a chain of stores in [[Katanga Province]] and became involved in politics.

==Political career==
He founded the [[CONAKAT|Confédération des associations tribales du Katanga]] (CONAKAT) party, with [[Godefroid Munongo]]. CONAKAT promoted a federal Congo independent of the [[Belgian colonial empire]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=qqWIvIAe2h4C The Congo from Leopold to Kabila], Georges Nzongola-Ntalaja, 2002, {{ISBN|1-84277-053-5}}, accessed February 2009</ref>

CONAKAT won control of the Katanga provincial legislature in the May 1960 general elections. One month later, the Congo became an independent republic. Tshombe became President of Katanga.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rulers.org/cngkprov.html|title=Congo (Kinshasa) provinces|website=www.rulers.org|access-date=2017-09-17}}</ref>

In the resulting [[Congo Crisis|strife and chaos following independence]], CONAKAT declared the [[State of Katanga]]'s secession from the rest of the Congo. The Christian, [[anti-communism|anti-communist]] pro-Western Tshombe declared, "We are seceding from chaos." Favoring continued ties with [[Belgium]], he asked the Belgian government to send military officers to recruit and train a Katangese army.

==Independence leader==
[[File:Tshombe with Operation Unokat casualty cropped.jpg|thumb|Tshombe in Katanga, 1962]]
Tshombe demanded [[UN]] recognition for independent Katanga, and he announced that any intervention by UN troops would be met with force.<ref>{{Cite news |last= |first= |agency=Reuters |date=21 July 1960 |title=Katanga Premier Warns U.N. Force |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1960/07/21/99759909.pdf |newspaper=The New York Times |location=New York |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=10 January 2016 }}</ref> Nonetheless, Congolese Prime Minister [[Patrice Lumumba]] and his successor, [[Cyrille Adoula]], successfully requested intervention from UN forces. UN forces were sent under the direction of UN Secretary-General Dag Hammarskjöld.

Lumumba's government was overthrown, and Lumumba taken prisoner by [[Mobutu]] and detained at Camp Hardy in [[Thysville]]. {{ill|Harold d'Aspremont Lynden|nl|Harold Charles d'Aspremont Lynden}} (Belgian minister for African Affairs) sent a highly confidential telegram on 16 January 1961 to the government in [[Léopoldville]] (President [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]] and Mobutu) to send Lumumba to Katanga. That would have stemmed from Lumumba's increasing popularity among soldiers, who might release him. Meanwhile, soldier mutinies and unrest increased by the day, at Prison Camp Hardy in Thysville. The telegram has still not been shown to exist.

While being flown in a [[Sabena]] DC-4 air plane to Katanga, Lumumba was beaten by the Congolese soldiers escorting him. In custody in Katanga, Lumumba was visited by Katangese notables and Belgian officers, who included Tshombe, [[Godefroid Munongo]], Kibwe, Kitenge, Grandelet, Son, Gat, Huyghé, Tignée, Verscheure, Segers and Rougefort. Lumumba's execution was carried out by a firing squad led by a Belgian mercenary, Julien Gat.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Assassination-Lumumba-Ludo-Witte/dp/1859844103 ''The Assassination of Lumumba''], [[Ludo De Witte]], 2003, {{ISBN|1-85984-410-3}}</ref>

==Later life==
[[File:Moise Tshombe touring Stanleyville.jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Tshombe touring Stanleyville in 1964]]
In 1963, UN forces succeeded in suppressing Katanga, driving Tshombe into exile in [[Northern Rhodesia]], later to [[Spain]]. In July 1964, he returned to the Congo to serve as prime minister in a new coalition government.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} Tshombe's national support was derived from the backing of provincial political bosses, customary chiefs, and foreign financial interests.{{sfn|Semonin|1968|p=20}} He was dismissed from his position in October 1965 by President Kasa-Vubu. In late 1965, General Mobutu, who had staged a successful coup against Kasa-Vubu, brought charges of treason against Tshombe, who again fled the country and settled in [[Francoist Spain]].

In 1967, he was sentenced to death ''in absentia''. On 30 June 1967, he was in a [[British Aerospace BAe 125|Hawker Siddeley jet aircraft]] that was [[aircraft hijacking|hijack]]ed by Francis Bodenan, an agent of the [[SDECE]] of [[France]]. According to the Congolese government, Tshombe was going to Africa.<ref name = "gibb">{{cite book | last = Gibbs | first = David N.  | title = The Political Economy of Third World Intervention | publisher = University of Chicago Press | year = 1991 | pages = 152, 167–168 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NgN64EXv8mgC&pg=PA152&dq=Moise+Tshombe#PPA168,M1 | isbn = 0-226-29071-9}}</ref>

Tshombe was taken to [[Algeria]], jailed, and placed under house arrest. The pilots of the plane, Britons Trevor Coppleston and David Taylor, were released and returned to the United Kingdom. The Congolese government demanded his extradition to Congo, and his Western supporters agitated for his release.<ref name = "gibb"/> The Algerians resisted both demands.

== Death and legacy ==
{{quote|"Moïse Tshombe nearly became the 'savior' of the Congo on his return from exile. But history decided otherwise, and the Congolese people found themselves under the leadership of Mobutu".|[[Thomas Kanza]], 1972{{sfn|Kanza|1994|p=327}}}}
Tshombe died in 1969, the official cause of death was listed as "death from heart failure". He was buried in a [[Methodist]] service at [[Etterbeek]] Cemetery, near [[Brussels]], Belgium.<ref>{{Cite news |last= |first= |agency=UPI |date=6 July 1969 |title=Tshombe is Buried in Brussels; Sons Weep at His Grave |url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1969/07/06/89009941.html?pageNumber=6 |newspaper=The New York Times |location=New York |publisher=The New York Times Company |page=6 |accessdate=18 January 2016 }}</ref> Due to his role in the death of Lumumba and association with Western interests, Tshombe's surname became synonymous with "sellout" to black African nationalists.{{sfn|Sibanda|2005|p=116}}{{sfn|Fouéré|2015|p=158}}{{efn|A derivative of Tshombe's name, ''chombe'', was incorporated into the [[Shona language]] as a word for "sellout". ''Kuchomba'' is the verb form.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.thepatriot.co.zw/old_posts/tshombe-geneva-and-detente-in-the-village/| title = Tshombe, Geneva and détente in the village| last = Pekeshe| first = Munhamu| date = 15 January 2015| website = The Patriot| access-date = 15 May 2018}}</ref>}}

